<p class="p2"><br></p>
<p class="p1"><b>Breeding</b></p>
<p class="p2"><br></p>
<p class="p1">The male’s foghorn-like boom in the evenings during the breeding season (June to February) is the best sign of the bittern’s presence. He booms to attract females, and to guard the territory from other males.</p>
<p class="p2"><br></p>
<p class="p1">While the male defends the territory, the female bittern makes the nest, breaking down reeds to form a platform 25–30 centimetres above the water. She incubates the eggs and feeds the hatchlings.</p>
<p class="p2"><br></p>
<p class="p1"><b>Rear guard action</b></p>
<p class="p2"><br></p>
<p class="p1">Māori believed that the bittern made a booming noise from its backside, with its sharp bill stuck into the ground. The Ngāti Awa historian and <i>tohunga</i> (priest) Hāmiora Pio suggested that these blasts were caused by the bird struggling to overcome a writhing eel.</p>
<p class="p2"><br></p>
<p class="p1"><b>Population</b></p>
<p class="p2"><br></p>
<p class="p1">A census in 1980 found just 600–700 birds, thinly scattered over the North and South islands. Their numbers have fallen due to drainage of wetlands, and they are nationally endangered.</p>
<p class="p1">Australasian bitterns are native to New Zealand, southern Australia, New Caledonia and the Loyalty Islands</p>
<p class="p2"><br></p>
